Engine may stall FAA urgently orders to check 2,000 Boeing airliners-Xinhuanet
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic airliners registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valves of the airliners may cause the engines to stop in the air.
The FAA said that so far, it has received 4 reports of 737NG and 737Classic aircraft engine parking in the air, so it has made an emergency inspection request. The inspection objects are passenger aircraft that have been parked continuously for 7 days or more and passenger aircraft that have flown less than 11 times so far after re-entering the flight.
The FAA warned that if the stage 5 check valves of all two engines of the airliner are corroded, they may get stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to completely lose power and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulatory agency ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace this key component before the passenger plane is put into service again.
Boeing responded later that day that the COVID-19 outbreak had reduced travel demand, and many passenger planes had been sealed or used less, and " check valves were more likely to be corroded. "
Boeing also said that it has advised air operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the order. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that passenger planes owned by major US airline operators usually fly multiple times a day, but after the outbreak of the COVID-19 epidemic, a large number of passenger planes were grounded; With the recent slow growth of passenger travel demand, some passenger planes have been put into operation again.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline said in a statement that one of its passenger planes was en route from Seattle, Washington to Austin, Texas on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled, and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the passenger plane's engine and had inspected the engines of six passenger planes in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that there was no engine stalling associated with the air check valve on their airliners.
Four American Airlines airliners will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines airliners will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 passenger planes, but did not say whether there had been engine failure.
According to many media reports, the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another impact on Boeing.
A Boeing 737MAX passenger plane of Indonesian Lion Airlines and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of passenger planes were subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year, and resumed production in May.
FAA Director Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA " made a mistake " in supervising Boeing with regard to the 737MAX passenger plane.
