The United States launches countervailing investigation against China for the first time with " undervalued RMB exchange rate "
In response to the recent announcement by the US Department of Commerce, it decided to launch an anti-dumping and countervailing investigation on tie-in (tie-in) products originating in China, and to launch an investigation on the " undervalued RMB exchange rate " project.
China's Ministry of Commerce pointed out that this is the first time that the United States has filed an investigation into the so-called " undervalued RMB exchange rate " project in a countervailing case, which China firmly opposes.
China's Ministry of Commerce issued a special press release on the evening of the 23rd, saying that China implements a managed floating exchange rate system based on market supply and demand, adjusted with reference to a basket of currencies, and the market plays a decisive role in the formation of the exchange rate.
The press release stressed that on the whole, the RMB exchange rate is at a reasonable equilibrium level and has not been undervalued.
Since 2005, the RMB has appreciated by more than 17% against the US dollar.
According to data released by the Bank for International Settlements, from the beginning of 2005 to May 2020, the nominal effective exchange rate of the RMB appreciated by 38% and the real effective exchange rate by 49%, making it the strongest currency in the G20 economies and one of the currencies with the largest appreciation in the world.
The Ministry of Commerce pointed out that the exchange rate issue is beyond the competence of members to conduct countervailing investigations in accordance with WTO rules.
The United States amended its regulations in February this year to conduct countervailing investigations on the exchange rates of other countries. It has been suspected of violating WTO rules and has been opposed by many parties.
The press release stated that even in accordance with U.S. regulations, the applicant's complaint contained a large number of errors and did not possess the necessary countervailing elements such as financial assistance, granting of benefits and specificity.
China urges the US to abide by existing international rules and stop conducting countervailing investigations into the so-called " undervalued RMB exchange rate. "
Affected by the further rise in tensions between China and the United States, the offshore and onshore RMB exchange rates against the US dollar fell sharply on the 22nd, and both fell below the 7.0 yuan mark against the US dollar.
Whether the US Department of Commerce's move is intended to force up the RMB deserves attention.
The spot exchange rate of RMB against the US dollar rose above the 7.0 mark on the 23rd to close at 6.9961.
The central parity rate of the RMB against the US dollar, which is officially regulated, was lowered by 17 basis points to 6.9938 on the 24th.
