Hoh Xil Tibetan antelope enters migration season-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of Hoh Xil Management Office in the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that monitoring showed that Tibetan antelopes who had migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth were gradually ending their births and began to return to their original habitat with their cubs.
Monitoring images near Wudaoliang Protection Station show that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led 3 Tibetan antelope cubs through 3002 kilometers of Qinghai-Tibet Highway and Wudaoliang North Bridge on Qinghai-Tibet Railway. Tibetan antelopes have begun to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the relocating sheep accounts for one quarter to one fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope herds.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: " In the early stage of migration, Tibetan antelopes face a higher risk of predation, so the number of cubs in the flock will be relatively small, and there may even be no cubs. "
According to the statistics of Hoh Xil Management Office of Yangtze River Source Park of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning has been increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning was 4860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lian Xinming said: " It is expected that the migration of Tibetan antelopes this year will end in early September, and the number of relocated Tibetan antelopes is expected to continue to increase. "
Tibetan antelope is a national-level protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from the Sanjiangyuan of Qinghai, Qiangtang of Tibet, Aljinshan of Xinjiang and other places go to Zhuonai Lake in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on Tibetan antelope protection in China and a researcher at Shaanxi Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: " Tibetan antelope migration is a process in which female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitat with their cubs after giving birth. At first, the relocation group leaving the litter site is relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats along different paths according to different geographical populations. "
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelope herds, the reporter learned that the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to continue to carry out video monitoring and patrols in the main relocation areas.
If Tibetan antelopes are found trying to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to let the sheep safely pass through the wildlife passage and ensure that they are as little disturbed by humans as possible on the way back.
So, how to relieve heat in daily life?
Experts suggest that when going out in summer, try to avoid the high temperature period, and it is best not to walk or work in the hot sun around noon, because the sun is the strongest during this period, and the possibility of heat stroke is higher.
If you have to go out at this time, you must do a good job of protection, such as playing a parasol, wearing a sun hat, and wearing sunglasses. If possible, it is best to apply sunscreen to prevent injuries.
Clothes try to choose light-colored, breathable cotton, hemp, silk texture, wear less chemical fiber clothing, so as not to lose heat in time when sweating a lot, causing heatstroke.
In hot and sultry weather, you should prepare enough water to drink in time. Don't wait for thirst to drink water, because once you feel thirsty, your body is already short of water. Drink 150 ml to 200 ml of water each time. Drink warm boiled water, not ice water.
According to the temperature, ordinary people drink 1.5 to 2 liters of water a day, and high-temperature workers drink 3 to 5 liters of water a day.
When you sweat more, you can appropriately supplement some salt water to make up for the salt lost by the human body due to sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to lack of potassium in summer, which makes people feel tired and tired. Potassium-containing tea is an excellent summer drink.
In summer, eat more fruits and vegetables with high water content, such as lettuce, cucumber, tomato, etc.; Fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons, etc., with a water content of 80% to 90%, can be used to supplement water; Dairy products cannot only replenish water, but also meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, people working in high temperature environment should appropriately supplement drinks containing potassium, magnesium and other elements.
In summer, the days are long and nights are short, the temperature is high, the metabolism of the human body is strong, the consumption is also large, and it is easy to feel tired.
Adequate sleep can relax all systems of the brain and body, which is not only conducive to work and study, but also a measure to prevent heatstroke.
Experts say that the best bedtime is from 22: 00 to 23: 00, and the best time to wake up is from 5: 30 to 6: 30.
Be careful not to lie under the air-conditioning vents and electric fans during sleep to avoid air-conditioning diseases and hot colds.
Experts suggest that people who are outdoors or doing high-temperature work can carry ten drops of water, Rendan, Patchouli Zhengqi Water or Patchouli Zhengqi Pills and other heatstroke prevention drugs with them, or place them in the nearest workplace and use them at any time to prevent heatstroke.
