Recently, a Brazilian study showed that hydroxychloroquine is ineffective for patients with mild to moderate new coronary pneumonia.
The study was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
Pakistani researchers divided 667 patients from 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted clinical trials; mainly compared the therapeutic effects of hydroxychloroquine alone or in combination with other antibiotics azithromycin, and analyzed whether it was helpful to improve patients with mild and moderate new coronary pneumonia.
The results show that hydroxychloroquine not only has no therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on organs.
This research was carried out by several authoritative hospitals in Brazil, such as Hospital Israel Albert Einstein, Heart Hospital (HCor), Hospital Sírio-Libanês, etc., in conjunction with the Brazilian Clinical Research Institute (BCRI) and the Brazilian Intensive Care Research Network (BRICNet).
